el emissions on an annual basis bring new renewable energy capacity to the grid  jpmorgan chase  co all rights reserved × start video overlay close video overlay turn captions on   show transcript end video overlay chase and current powered by ge collaborate to cut energy use in branches across the us chase and current powered by ge collaborate to cut energy use in branches across the us jpmorgan chase has entered the second phase of an ongoing collaboration with current powered by ge to install new energy management and digital technologies that will increase the energy efficiency of roughly  chase branches across the us chase’s new installation complements the bank’s ongoing commitment to sustainability which includes efforts to manage its buildings and branches more efficiently current’s new energy management system will utilize sensors software and lighting controls to help chase branches reduce electric and gas consumption by  percent and water from irrigation systems by  percent the bank is also working with current to pilot an installation of solar panels at chase branches the first phase of this collaboration included the world’s largest led lighting installation to date  branches have been retrofitted with led lighting helping to cut chase’s lighting energy consumption by  percent or the equivalent of taking nearly  cars off the road jpmorgan chase is on target to reach its goal to reduce greenhouse gas emissions  percent below  levels by  and continues to offset  percent of emissions generated by employee air travel on an annual basis in addition to the new solar pilot the company promotes renewable energy by supporting projects that bring new renewable energy capacity to the grid view text version read more about the collaboration between jpmorgan chase and current powered by ge ﻿ related stories related stories click to hide the content below click to show the content below technology connects ideas and colleagues across the globe jpmorgan chase global t